The following is a doc on how to use all the various calendar functions
provided by the astronomy and events daemons.  To use ANY of these
functions, you must first:

#include <daemons.h>

in any file that is going to be calling a function.  Next, depending
on what information you want, you can call the following functions.
Note, to use many of these functions, you must call them in the format
shown. I.e. for many, you must pass the current time as part of the query.
To get the actual names of the days of the week and months of the year,
look at the help file called "calendar". I.e. "help calendar".


To determine the numerical minute of the hour:
  minute = EVENTS_D->query_minutes(time());


To determine the numerical hour of the day:
  hour = EVENTS_D->query_hour(time());
 Note: This will return a result on a scale of 0 to 19 hours.
       if you want to have it on a am, pm type of scale, you
       will need to add something like the following to your code:

          if (hour == 0) {
            hour = 12;
            tod = " Fore High-Sun";
          }
          else if (hour > 11) {
            hour = hour - 12;
            if (hour == 0) hour = 12;
            tod = " Nights Watch";
          }
          else tod = " Fore High-Sun";
          write("|CK0    and the time is: "+hour+":");
          if (mmnt < 10)
            write("|CK00"+mmnt+tod+".\n");
          else
            write("|CK0"+mmnt+tod+".\n");
         return 1;
        }

  There are probobly better ways to do this, so if you think of one
  go ahead and use it.  This is just here as an example.



To get the Name of the day:
  day_name = EVENTS_D->query_day_name(time());


To get the numerical day of the month:
  day_number = EVENTS_D->query_day(time());


To get the Name of the month:
  month = EVENTS_D->query_month_name(time());
 Note: There are 10 months in a year.


To determine what week of the month it is:
    week_num = EVENTS_D->query_week(time());
 Note: There are 3 weeks to a month.

To get the numeric year:
  year = EVENTS_D->query_year(time());


To get the time of day in string format:
  what = EVENTS_D->query_time_of_day();
 This will return one of the following strings depending on the
        time of day:  dawn, day twilight, night.


If, for some reason, you want the exact second since the the calendar
        system started:
  now = EVENTS_D->query_now();


To get the numeric phase of a given moon, (where str = the name of the moon you
     want to see):
  phase = ASTRONOMY_D->query_phase(str);
 The moon names are: "dailos" "markas" and "tekal".


To get the string name of the phase of a given moon:
  phase = ASTRONOMY_D->query_phase_name(ASTRONOMY_D->query_phase(str));
 where 'str' is the name of the moon you want to get the phase for.
 The moon names are: "dailos" "markas" and "tekal".


